Do you train with or without headphones? The poll in my story is about 50/50. ➡️ saw this awesome saying from @behaviorhack about normalizing silence.

I find myself often feeling over stimulated from the constant noise of technology. Without technology, I wouldn't be able to remotely run a business. With that, it's increasingly hard to not feel constantly bombarded. I believe I speak for many when we've been feeling this way since the pandemic.

3 things I do religiously that help give me more silence in a loud world.

1) do not disturb: I love to use my phone to take pictures & videos but hate being interrupted and taking time out being present. I mark certain contacts as "favorites" so they can get through OR when clients are cutting weight/competing of course. Everything else gets treated like an e-mail, I'll respond during a designated time. 

2) no headphones when working out: When I did a strength sport I never wore headphones, when I did bodybuilding I felt I needed music. I recently ditched the headphones again. It's been a positive experience.

3) An auto response on what's app. Set boundaries. People don't have access to you 24/7. 🔊this is for anyone in the service industry or with clients.

📸 @theactivity

315lbs x 18 this past Friday at the Rhino cage at the Olympia. This was special to me because earlier in the year I decided I didn't feel the need to compete any longer. Lifting was for me.

5 weeks prior to this when @stanefferding invited me as a guest lifter and I could choose what lift, I knew it had to be squats. Squats resonated with me as they've been a mantra to me since I started doing them at 14, "when life gets heavy just stand back up."

I had this crazy idea and set a goal for 20 reps. The most I've ever done in training was 12. I was in Australia for the majority of this training and last minute prep. When I got back home, I was dealing with an ongoing knee and IT band issue, so I changed my technique last minute (I prefer high bar).

Although I didn't hit my goal of 20, I knew from my own data and body, anything over 15 I had to be pleased with. This day though, it felt heavy after rep 2, we all know that's just how it is some days. None of these reps were speedy. I was utilizing the @tomplatz breathing technique that @jailhousestrong taught me.

Contrary to belief, I do not go to a dark place when I lift, it's the opposite for me. I go to a place that's honoring my mind and the power of belief. Some things can't be explained. I love strength training and everything it continues to teach me and how it always keeps me humble.

On Jan 23 of this year strength legend @budjeffries passed away. Before I did this set, I thought about this year and what he said and set my intention for this lift: "Never never never give up as long as there's breath left in your body".

Thank you to @stanefferding for hosting this, all the amazing other guest lifters that I get to call friends. @cerberus_strength_usa for their endless support and making it so my knees could do this. @shway89 for coming to visit and all your support right along with @hamstringpapa_

12/17 was a day I'll never forget. The series of events that happened after this heightened my spiritual belief. I'll keep that part brief on social media but squats are part of my religion.

Dear anyone reading this,

You are not alone. You're never alone.

I didn't send Christmas cards this year and I didn't take an annual matching PJ picture with @smell__the__rosies I can tell you what I did do though. 

This isn't advice, this is just sharing vulnerability, something I've learned is much more powerful than putting up a front.

I've cried uncontrollablly. I stayed up until early morning hours because I couldn't stop those ugly tears from taking over.

I lost people close to me and couldn't go to their funerals. I felt the impact of friends and clients who lost loved ones.

I learned to be without my best friend: my mom. Although she was just a phone call away, 10 months is the longest I've gone without seeing her. She was faced with her own health issues and there was nothing I could do but offer support from afar. 

I had those days where I've questioned my purpose and my worth. I've worried about money and felt like a failure for being 30 years old, not owning a house and paying way to much in rent. I've constantly asked myself if I'll ever have a place I call home or have my own family.

I've set goals and then realized they weren't aligned with who I wanted to be. I let go of the need to always win and be in competition with myself. "Rather than love, than money, than fame, give me truth". 

I felt the rain on my face and at one point didn't feel any sunshine for 3 weeks straight (PNW).

I've met all walks of life in my adventure and 3 cross country moves. Some will be friends for life, some were just here for a season.

I've read more. I've written more. Some words I share, some I will keep private. To me, writing comes from the soul. There's energy and power in the words you both write and speak

I've let go of material possessions.

I've let go without having closure.

I've surrendered without knowing what's next.

I've realized even through a storm, a flower will bloom.

Most importantly, I've grasped something not everyone can: If you find peace in the little things life gives you, you'll realize the present is the biggest gift of them all.

To strap up or not? A common question and even the source of some internet fights in my comment section. 🤣 Here's why I wear the multi grips and why it's OK to strap up. 

I work grip on so many other movements that when I'm rowing (especially a few sets in as grip fatigues) I want to make sure my primary focus is strengthening my back. Putting the straps on allows me to focus on the target muscles and not have to skip out on a few reps due to forearms/grips fatiguing. 

I'd rather handle more volume with my accessory work than have grip be a limiting factor. As someone that trained strongman style for years, I frowned upon any rows not using my full body and disregarded straps unless it was an axle pull. 😑 Since I've adopted a more open mindset with training principles, I'm way stronger and my physique is more developed and balanced now.

These are the @cerberus_strength_usa multi-grips. Remmeber they're a TOOL for training and shouldn't become a crutch. Safest bet is to do your first few sets without, then throw them on. "BDimez10" will save you on all gear, can still buy yourself gifts for the new year!💰💰💰

Upper body press movement! If I could only pick 1, it would be this:1/2 kneeling landmine press 👑. 5 reasons why ⬇️⬇️⬇️ ⁣
⁣
Today was my only structured upper body push day for the week. Far cry from doing pull ups every single day. For the first time in my life, I'm trying to downsize my upper body a bit. I've been dealing with numb hands for awhile now and I feel I've maxed out my upper body size past the point of healthy -for my new training goals.Once upon a time I was self conscience of my twig arms, LOL. ⁣
⁣
Anyways, here are the 𝗿𝗲𝗮𝘀𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝘄𝗵𝘆 𝗜 𝗽𝗶𝗰𝗸𝗲𝗱 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗲𝘅𝗲𝗿𝗰𝗶𝘀𝗲 as I feel you get the most bang for your buck. ⁣
⁣
1) this can substitute for all overhead work as it's more horizontal in nature ⁣
⁣
2) no pressure on low back (unlike standing presses & bench press). With 3 lower body days, I don't need any more pressure on my lower back. ⁣
⁣
3) as a unilateral movement it helps left and right imbalances which every one has to some degree. ⁣
⁣
4) builds motor control, can't just bang out the reps: must control the press and the eccentric motion in scapula & triceps ⁣
⁣
5) the 1/2 kneeling position works core stability and glute engagement. ⁣
⁣
I'm keeping volume high with 4 x 15 per set. ⁣
⁣
The cool thing is that I'm confident I won't lose much strength. If and when I do decide I want to put up some big numbers overhead, I know I'm keeping a base to do so. ⁣

A different kind of #transformation

Yesterday morning in Vegas ➡️1 year ago in RI after I just finished decorating my new home.

Body composition and hair length similar but what you can't see is the letting go of ego and losing my connection to material things. 

I've spent a great deal of the last year angry that I lost everything I worked so hard to build and have. My material possessions ranging from nice furniture, nice cars, designer clothes and hundreds of pairs of shoes symbolized to me that I could make it on my own. 

When I was forced to unexpectedly evacuate my brand new home and there was a housing shortage in the northeast, I went into an old pattern of survival mode. Pretty sure my landlord follows me on IG so, hi. 👋

Selling or donating everything I owned in 5 days, leaving the community I had built, leaving my family, all for a chance (when I'm not one to gamble) was the riskiest thing I've ever done.

Moving 3 times in 2022 to 3 different places in the US where I had no familiarity and still being able to grow my business has been an accomplishment I'm most proud of thus far.

My experience and lessons have lead me to exactly where I'm meant to be right now. I've further strengthened my relationship to nature and whoever is up there responsible for daily beautiful skies (sup sky daddy) 🙏. I finally accepted what it means to surrender.

What hasn't changed: daily walks/rucks and the best posing from @smell__the__rosies 💞

Take that leap of faith and never forget as you're transforming there are parts of yourself that need to die in order to grow.

Back with some requested #OnlyPans Banana Coffee dairy free protein bread. Save & share if you want more.

I followed instructions for once and didn't just throw stuff together 🤷🏼‍♀️

3 large overly ripe bananas 
2.5c oats
3 scoops of @granitesupplements (I used the chocolate plant protein to make it dairy free) can use any flavor as they all mix well. BDimez10 will save $
2 eggs
1.5 cup unsweetened vanilla almond milk
¼ cup sugar free syrup (honey works too)
1 tsp vanilla extract
½ cup walnuts
2 tsp cinnamon
¼ tsp sea salt
1 tbsp coffee grounds (optional)
1 tsp baking powder
1 tsp vanilla seeds

In a small bowl mix together the dry ingredients: oats, protein powder, and spices
In a large bowl mash the bananas, add in the eggs, almond milk, syrup and walnuts
Combine wet & dry to a baking dish (spray PAM or something similar so doesnt stick)
Bake in oven at 375 for 30 mins for a gooey texture, longer if you prefer a denser bread.

Optional toppings: nut butter or syrup

Makes for an excellent post workout treat, dessert, or delicious and easy way to get down some calories.

Even though I’m not nearly as strong as I once was or as lean, I have a newfound respect for my body and it’s capabilities. I have tons of injuries that I navigate around (a knee that probably needs replacing and several herniated discs.). The older you get, the more life compounds and the harder things will get. I try not to complain about them but rather work on solutions because there is always a way to work around hardships. 

My only training goals have been to :
👉shrink my upper body 
👉add some size to my legs & glutes peach 🍑 Why? Because I can and want to. 
I’ve been doing LESS THAN I EVER HAVE. I train 4-5 days a week &  walk or ruck everyday. I was an avid overtrained my whole life (endurance athlete originally). 

As you age and still want to prioritize training for all the good it does, I feel it’s important to check yourself and not compare to where you used to be. Just remember that training is for you and no one else. 

Sacred training rules to honor: 
✅it’s OK to train with no competition in sight
✅still structure your training so you have a plan
✅set goals with no hard finish line 
✅goals that are important to YOU and you only 
✅prioritize YOUR SESSIONS, if you’re reading this you can make time 
✅always push for that last rep 😉

Growing up, I hated how skinny my arms were and starting in middle school after track practice, I’d do curls almost everyday. I hated them because of all the unsolicited comments: Big arm girl, Brittany Biceps etc (I can laugh at them now). 

Last year, I decided to not train arms and concentrated on growing my legs and glutes (which doesn’t come as easy). It was a little science experiment, and I was happy with how I was able to balance out my physique. However, I really missed my strength and being able to bust out weighted pull ups and dips on a whim. 

Now that I’m back to training full body, I’ve come to the conclusion that: 

Strong is powerful.

Beauty is always in the eyes of the beholder. 

If people want to stare, give them something to stare at.

But most importantly:
👉Minimizing oneself for an ideal is bullshit. 👈

Say it louder for the people in the back.
